From:E_K_S
Hi Madharry - Yes SIL has had a great run especially that it has almost come
round trip from it's high of $25.70 on April 10, 2006 and you were able to buy
in near the low! The key to a great investment is to have an exit plan and
diversify into several companies that continue to grow earnings over the long
run.

Check out the performance of the conglomerate mining and resource stocks over
five years compared to SIL. Some of these large companies include RIO
(Companhia Vale do Rio Doce), BHP (BHP Billiton Ltd.) and AAUK (ANGLO AM PLC
ADR).
http://finance.yahoo.com/charts#chart4:symbol=sil;range=5y;compare=aauk+bhp+rio
indicator=volume;charttype=line;crosshair=on;logscale=on;source=undefined

You might consider when you hit your long term holding period, to peel off a
few shares and move some of those profits into a large diversified conglomerate
resource and mining company. This way you pay a maximum 15% long term capital
gains tax, diversify into a company that has exposure to several valuable
metals and pay you an annual dividend while you hold.

You definitely have hit a home run on part one. I have always found that the
hard part is to find undervalued companies that can keep compounding their
earnings and grow over several years.

I am always looking for those undervalued gems that will grow earnings for
years. Also, no matter how much I like the company, I limit my total investment
to less that 9% of my portfolio. Most of my individual company positions total
only 3% of my investment portfolio value and when they run higher to over
7%-8%, I peel off shares and rebalance the portfolio..

Good work on your SIL pick.

